at the University of Pittsburgh, and associate director of basic

537
00:30:21.622 --> 00:30:24.032
research at the UPMC Hillman Cancer Center.

538
00:30:24.122 --> 00:30:27.682
Today I'm going to be talking to you about the metabolic

539
00:30:27.742 --> 00:30:31.582
consequences of T cell exhaustion and how that matters in

540
00:30:33.542 --> 00:30:35.072
cancer and cancer immunotherapy.

541
00:30:35.922 --> 00:30:38.242
These are my disclosures, none of which are relevant for today's talk.

542
00:30:39.142 --> 00:30:40.382
So the underlying

543
00:30:41.461 --> 00:30:45.062
basis of immune metabolism is that immune

544
00:30:45.082 --> 00:30:48.342
responses require a massive amount of energy.

545
00:30:49.082 --> 00:30:52.962
So your naive T-- And part of the reason is because the immune system sits

546
00:30:52.982 --> 00:30:56.471
between two poles of extreme quiescence and extreme activation.

547
00:30:56.502 --> 00:30:59.562
So naive T cells potentially wait for a lifetime in extreme

548
00:30:59.582 --> 00:31:01.802
quiescence. They divide once a year.

549
00:31:02.322 --> 00:31:03.862
So they don't really do a whole lot.

550
00:31:03.902 --> 00:31:05.092
However, when they get activated,

551
00:31:06.422 --> 00:31:10.272
very, very rapidly, they grow for 24 hours and then divide every

552
00:31:10.302 --> 00:31:14.002
three hours for a solid week. So they really exist

553
00:31:14.482 --> 00:31:18.192
in these two amazing states. Now, when they are activated, they're

554
00:31:18.202 --> 00:31:21.262
differentiating and acquiring new effector functions.

555
00:31:21.282 --> 00:31:24.202
And so they don't just need to proliferate, although they're doing a lot, they're

556
00:31:24.222 --> 00:31:27.562
using a lot of energy to proliferate, but they also need to make morphologic

557
00:31:27.622 --> 00:31:31.562
changes to move around the body and to intrinsically alter the

558
00:31:31.692 --> 00:31:32.252
epigenome.

559
00:31:33.372 --> 00:31:36.792
Effector T cells are extremely metabolically active while they are doing these

560
00:31:36.822 --> 00:31:40.802
jobs. But when that antigen gets cleared

561
00:31:41.042 --> 00:31:43.082
and they enter into their memory phase,

562
00:31:44.182 --> 00:31:47.902
they rewire their metabolism. And they really do this at the level of the

563
00:31:47.942 --> 00:31:51.702
mitochondria. They rewire their mitochondria so that they have volume,

564
00:31:51.882 --> 00:31:55.842
quality, and what we call respiratory capacity that you can measure

565
00:31:55.882 --> 00:31:59.842
using respirometry. This promotes longevity and increased readiness

566
00:31:59.862 --> 00:32:01.882
to respond to the antigen again,

567
00:32:02.962 --> 00:32:04.802
and that's been seen by several different groups.

568
00:32:05.202 --> 00:32:08.322
Meanwhile, exhausted T cells, which are essentially the product of a failed immune

569
00:32:08.362 --> 00:32:12.102
response in so many words, because the antigen doesn't go away,

570
00:32:12.572 --> 00:32:16.522
they have repressed mitochondrial and carbohydrate metabolism that both underlies

571
00:32:16.602 --> 00:32:20.171
how they become exhausted in the first place and why they fail to function when

572
00:32:20.182 --> 00:32:23.902
they get there. So we've been asking for the last dozen years or so,

573
00:32:24.262 --> 00:32:27.642
how do various metabolic environments shape T cell function and fates?

574
00:32:27.942 --> 00:32:29.882
And we're all talking today because we're thinking about the tumor

575
00:32:29.922 --> 00:32:32.762
microenvironments. This is a melanoma patient metastasis.

576
00:32:32.842 --> 00:32:36.742
It's a cutaneous metastasis, and this patient has been pulsed with a hypoxia tracer

577
00:32:36.782 --> 00:32:40.722
called piminidazole. And so you can actually visualize both the hypoxic core

578
00:32:40.742 --> 00:32:42.912
of the tumor, but also these areas of high

579
00:32:45.022 --> 00:32:47.022
metabolic activity, and you can find

580
00:32:48.742 --> 00:32:51.382
T cells that are engaging in these metabolic areas.

581
00:32:51.402 --> 00:32:54.662
And so this has been the study of many groups for quite some time, trying to

582
00:32:54.722 --> 00:32:56.782
understand how the tumor microenvironment

583
00:32:57.802 --> 00:32:59.482
metabolically alters its

584
00:33:00.322 --> 00:33:01.042
local milieu,

585
00:33:01.982 --> 00:33:05.582
and not only that, but what are the consequences for infiltrating immunity.

586
00:33:06.282 --> 00:33:09.742
And we can use measurements of tumor microenvironment metabolism to predict

587
00:33:09.782 --> 00:33:13.762
immunotherapy outcomes in many different types of cancer and in many different

588
00:33:13.802 --> 00:33:17.422
types of therapy. And we and others have shown that the various metabolic

589
00:33:17.462 --> 00:33:21.262
conditions in isolation can skew immunity toward different

590
00:33:21.282 --> 00:33:25.252
fates of T cells. These data are old now, but

591
00:33:25.252 --> 00:33:28.242
I still like to talk about them, is that if you look at T cells that infiltrate

592
00:33:28.252 --> 00:33:31.361
tumors, they do so at an extreme metabolic disadvantage.

593
00:33:31.382 --> 00:33:34.532
The T cells that we find infiltrating tumors have repressed

594
00:33:35.382 --> 00:33:38.912
abilities to take up carbohydrates like glucose, but they really show this

595
00:33:38.942 --> 00:33:40.642
dramatic mitochondrial atrophy.

596
00:33:41.242 --> 00:33:44.082
As you can see, these are kind of textbook mitochondria, but the T cells that we

597
00:33:44.122 --> 00:33:46.912
get from tumors have very, very small malformed mitochondria.

598
00:33:47.492 --> 00:33:51.332
And this happens across many different tumor indications and it actually correlates

599
00:33:51.342 --> 00:33:54.942
with responses to PD-1 blockade. At the steady state, though, the

600
00:33:54.982 --> 00:33:58.802
most severe mitochondrial dysfunction is seen in the

601
00:33:58.862 --> 00:34:01.642
most terminally differentiated exhausted T cells.

602
00:34:01.882 --> 00:34:05.642
Okay, so the terminally exhausted T cells, not the TPs, for instance.

603
00:34:06.082 --> 00:34:08.362
So what is exhaustion? It gets used a lot.

604
00:34:08.882 --> 00:34:11.962
This term gets used a lot, but it actually has a fairly defined definition.

605
00:34:12.022 --> 00:34:13.723
It happens when antigens don't go away.

606
00:34:13.942 --> 00:34:16.002
So it's first described in chronic viral infections.

607
00:34:16.862 --> 00:34:20.382
But we now know that we can characterize exhausted T cells, not just by these

608
00:34:20.402 --> 00:34:24.022
markers that are on their cell surface, but really it's a functional phenotype.

609
00:34:24.082 --> 00:34:27.022
It's the absence of the ability of T cells to do lots of different things.

610
00:34:27.102 --> 00:34:29.241
We count on our T cells to be kind of like Swiss Army knives.

611
00:34:29.283 --> 00:34:32.572
They make lots of different cytokines, and they kill, and they can

612
00:34:32.622 --> 00:34:35.842
self-renew. But exhausted T cells really just eke out a little bit of gamma

613
00:34:35.882 --> 00:34:37.982
interferon. They don't self-renew.

614
00:34:38.022 --> 00:34:39.882
They don't really kill targets very well.

615
00:34:39.962 --> 00:34:43.922
And they actually can acquire suppressive properties via generating adenosine.

616
00:34:44.982 --> 00:34:47.142
Importantly, this is not a functional state of T cells.

617
00:34:47.263 --> 00:34:50.102
They are a lineage that is commensurate with an epigenetic signature.

618
00:34:50.872 --> 00:34:52.842
And they are not the target of immunotherapy.

619
00:34:53.082 --> 00:34:57.042
In fact, where anti-PD-1 acts is on these progenitor-like exhausted T

620
00:34:57.122 --> 00:35:00.542
cells that actually induce their differentiation into

621
00:35:00.802 --> 00:35:04.242
cytolytic effectors and ultimately terminally exhausted T

622
00:35:04.322 --> 00:35:07.332
cells. And this is a progressive phenotype. It doesn't just click on.

623
00:35:07.362 --> 00:35:10.902
It happens over time and with tumor burden.

624
00:35:12.092 --> 00:35:15.132
So we asked, how does metabolic stress alter the differentiation to exhaustion?

625
00:35:15.462 --> 00:35:16.682
And we reported this a few years ago.

626
00:35:16.702 --> 00:35:20.562
We actually broke things down using an in vitro model system where

627
00:35:20.602 --> 00:35:24.122
we can exhaust otherwise healthy T cells by simply

628
00:35:24.262 --> 00:35:28.132
stimulating them continuously using off-the-shelf stimulatory magnetic beads,

629
00:35:28.402 --> 00:35:32.102
but doing that under hypoxic stress, just throwing the T cells into a

630
00:35:32.122 --> 00:35:35.482
hypoxia chamber. And what we're able to do is pretty faithfully

631
00:35:35.562 --> 00:35:39.422
recapitulate the terminally exhausted phenotype in fairly rapid succession.

632
00:35:39.722 --> 00:35:42.782
You can see that here by markers. But remember what I told you a couple slides ago,

633
00:35:43.102 --> 00:35:44.902
markers are only one part of the equation.

634
00:35:45.342 --> 00:35:48.082
But you can look at all of these different markers and their transcription factors,

635
00:35:48.322 --> 00:35:52.002
but really it is their polyfunctionality, the ability to secrete multiple

636
00:35:52.022 --> 00:35:55.722
cytokines per cell, that is severely attenuated when the T cells

637
00:35:55.762 --> 00:35:59.582
experience both persistent TCR stimulation and hypoxia

638
00:35:59.602 --> 00:36:03.490
concurrently.You can sequence the cells, and we've done so through single

639
00:36:03.570 --> 00:36:07.270
cell and RNA sequencing, as well as epigenetic analysis.

640
00:36:07.630 --> 00:36:11.270
And you can see that it's not just a combination of the continuous stimulation and

641
00:36:11.310 --> 00:36:13.170
hypoxia programs, but a unique,

642
00:36:14.990 --> 00:36:17.950
distinct transcriptional signature that defines these cells.

643
00:36:17.980 --> 00:36:21.910
And if you compare that transcriptional signature to TILs, you can see that we

644
00:36:21.950 --> 00:36:25.630
have very nice correlation with terminally exhausted T cells that we isolate

645
00:36:26.010 --> 00:36:27.910
ex vivo. Now, why am I telling you all this story?

646
00:36:28.010 --> 00:36:29.070
I thought I was talking about mitochondria.

647
00:36:29.950 --> 00:36:33.649
Well, as it turns out, we can use models like this to understand

648
00:36:33.730 --> 00:36:37.630
how mitochondria change as a consequence of continuous stimulation.

649
00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:38.520
And so here's

650
00:36:39.870 --> 00:36:43.190
just an initial summary that the continuous TCR stimulation promotes a

651
00:36:43.230 --> 00:36:47.159
mitochondrial phenotype that makes them sensitive to hypoxia, and it drives

652
00:36:47.170 --> 00:36:50.290
an exhausted-like phenotype. And we've shown in other

653
00:36:50.310 --> 00:36:53.990
publications that hypoxia

654
00:36:54.030 --> 00:36:57.990
produces ROS, it mimics chronic signaling, but it also alters

655
00:36:58.010 --> 00:36:59.670
the methylation state of the epigenome.

656
00:37:00.570 --> 00:37:03.090
Now, I told you, you came in here to talk about mitochondria.

657
00:37:03.130 --> 00:37:06.870
So this is now unpublished work, and so how does this happen?

658
00:37:07.090 --> 00:37:10.770
How do immunologic signals talk to the mitochondria and change them?

659
00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:14.970
Our data, we're now suggesting that unlike what we saw in 2016,

660
00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:18.370
these T cells were not losing their mitochondria.

661
00:37:18.690 --> 00:37:20.530
Their mitochondria were changing.

662
00:37:20.550 --> 00:37:24.350
And what do chronic and tonic TCR

663
00:37:24.370 --> 00:37:28.150
signals do to the mitochondria? And what does that mean for the

664
00:37:28.170 --> 00:37:31.400
cell? So in other words, how do immunologic signals crosstalk with both the

665
00:37:31.400 --> 00:37:33.110
nucleus and the mitochondrion?

666
00:37:34.110 --> 00:37:37.980
Now, unfortunately, because of fifth-grade science class, we have

667
00:37:38.030 --> 00:37:39.970
a very skewed view of what mitochondria do.

668
00:37:40.250 --> 00:37:43.270
I think you all, no matter if you're metabolism people or not, we all know what

669
00:37:43.310 --> 00:37:44.870
you're supposed to say about mitochondria.

670
00:37:45.710 --> 00:37:47.490
But it turns out we have a very skewed view.

671
00:37:47.590 --> 00:37:51.130
Yes, we do indeed have the ability to take

672
00:37:51.210 --> 00:37:55.180
pyruvates and make ATP in all of the ways that you remember and memorized when

673
00:37:55.210 --> 00:37:57.060
you were in undergraduate biochemistry.

674
00:37:57.410 --> 00:38:01.230
However, mitochondria are so much more than just the powerhouses.

675
00:38:01.450 --> 00:38:05.370
They regulate cell death, they buffer calcium and other second messengers,

676
00:38:05.610 --> 00:38:09.270
and they generate ROS that is very critical for biochemistry to be

677
00:38:09.310 --> 00:38:13.190
performed. But also mitochondria produce dozens of

678
00:38:13.230 --> 00:38:17.190
biomolecules that serve many purposes in the cell, and that makes them far more

679
00:38:17.230 --> 00:38:20.250
like processors than powerhouses, okay?

680
00:38:20.290 --> 00:38:23.170
They're a signaling router in so many ways.

681
00:38:23.450 --> 00:38:24.890
So we really wanted to take this on.

682
00:38:25.550 --> 00:38:28.430
And so one way we started to look at this is we went right back to the same old

683
00:38:28.450 --> 00:38:31.830
things we were doing, and we noticed something that if we sorted out the

684
00:38:31.890 --> 00:38:35.880
individual subsets of cells, the Tpex-like population, but also

685
00:38:35.890 --> 00:38:39.010
the more terminally exhausted T cells, and we went back to our electron

686
00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:41.550
microscopy, we were always focused on the mitochondria.

687
00:38:41.610 --> 00:38:45.590
But one thing that we found was that lymph node T cells have these

688
00:38:45.650 --> 00:38:49.310
small lipid droplets, but the Tpex population, they start to

689
00:38:49.330 --> 00:38:52.110
accumulate lipids. But look at the exhausted T cells.

690
00:38:52.170 --> 00:38:55.730
They have these giant lipid droplets everywhere throughout the

691
00:38:55.750 --> 00:38:59.470
cytosol of the cell. And you can even measure this by a dye called

692
00:38:59.510 --> 00:39:02.250
BODIPY that stains neutral lipids, and you can see exhausted T cells are just

693
00:39:02.390 --> 00:39:04.650
loaded with lipid. And you can, of course,

694
00:39:06.030 --> 00:39:09.450
look at this even by flow cytometry, just by staining them with BODIPY.

695
00:39:09.790 --> 00:39:13.390
We also saw an accumulation of acetylated proteins across the

696
00:39:13.410 --> 00:39:17.100
entire proteome as T cells progressed to this terminally exhausted

697
00:39:17.150 --> 00:39:20.930
state. So this was interesting. These cells were not like not taking up

698
00:39:20.970 --> 00:39:24.359
carbon. They were actually full of carbon. So what was happening there?

699
00:39:25.370 --> 00:39:28.010
We could absolutely reproduce this in our in vitro system.

700
00:39:28.430 --> 00:39:31.790
So chronic stimulation could drive a little bit on its own, but if you added

701
00:39:31.810 --> 00:39:35.280
hypoxic stress, the T cells accumulated lipids and they

702
00:39:35.790 --> 00:39:38.930
accumulated the acetylated lysine across their proteome.

703
00:39:38.950 --> 00:39:41.110
So what was actually happening here, and how was this happening?

704
00:39:41.150 --> 00:39:43.970
So we wanted to look at the mitochondria of these cells, and we've done this both

705
00:39:43.990 --> 00:39:46.510
by RNA sequencing and by proteomics.

706
00:39:46.570 --> 00:39:50.520
And here was our hypothesis, that good effector memory like T cells,

707
00:39:50.890 --> 00:39:54.590
their mitochondria were places where carbon went to be burned to

708
00:39:54.630 --> 00:39:58.210
generate energy. However, exhausted T cells, their

709
00:39:58.230 --> 00:40:01.670
mitochondria may be more

710
00:40:01.680 --> 00:40:05.590
exporters. And this is absolutely borne out by looking at the family

711
00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:09.150
of genes that actually exchange carbon in and out of the mitochondria.

712
00:40:09.190 --> 00:40:13.170
This is the SLC25 family. And for the rest of the talk, I'm going to focus

713
00:40:13.210 --> 00:40:17.049
on the canonical member of this family called SLC25A1, which

714
00:40:17.070 --> 00:40:20.609
gets activated in effector memory T cells but stays highly

715
00:40:20.710 --> 00:40:24.170
upregulated as T cells become exhausted in tumors.

716
00:40:24.230 --> 00:40:26.770
So what is this 25A1, and why are we interested in it?

717
00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:29.590
Well, it encodes a citrate carrier.

718
00:40:30.450 --> 00:40:34.030
The citrate carrier. The mitochondrial citrate carrier, which removes

719
00:40:34.090 --> 00:40:37.670
citrate from the TCA cycle and it enters into the

720
00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:41.550
cytosol of cells. In the cytosol of cells, citrate can

721
00:40:42.050 --> 00:40:46.030
be converted back into acetyl-CoA, where it either forms lipids through

722
00:40:46.070 --> 00:40:49.890
de novo lipogenesis or acetylates proteins, the two

723
00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:53.690
things that we saw occurring in T cells as they progress to

724
00:40:53.730 --> 00:40:54.230
exhaustion.

725
00:40:55.290 --> 00:40:59.040
And we could show that while activation can acutely

726
00:40:59.090 --> 00:41:02.910
turn on the mitochondrial citrate carrier, chronic stimulation and especially

727
00:41:02.950 --> 00:41:06.880
hypoxic stress drove the persistent upregulation of this

728
00:41:06.910 --> 00:41:10.450
citrate carrier, providing an exit for carbon

729
00:41:10.490 --> 00:41:13.830
outside of the mitochondria and outside of the TCA cycle.

730
00:41:15.530 --> 00:41:15.690
So,

731
00:41:16.570 --> 00:41:18.390
could we actually see the citrate leaving

732
00:41:20.410 --> 00:41:21.710
the mitochondria and going to the cytosol?

733
00:41:22.010 --> 00:41:23.630
Well, we'd have to fractionate cells to do this.

734
00:41:23.670 --> 00:41:27.110
And if you've ever looked at a T cell under the microscope, it's about all nucleus

735
00:41:27.170 --> 00:41:30.490
and a tiny little bit of cytosol. So you can't really fractionate them.

736
00:41:30.810 --> 00:41:32.110
But Bing Zhang in the lab

737
00:41:33.490 --> 00:41:35.230
was able to repurpose a

738
00:41:36.430 --> 00:41:39.910
citrate sensor that is based on circularly permutated

739
00:41:40.150 --> 00:41:44.020
GFP, and we were able to transduce T cells and then park the sensor either in

740
00:41:44.050 --> 00:41:46.630
the cytosol or in the mitochondria of T cells.

741
00:41:46.650 --> 00:41:49.880
And you can see, consistent with our hypotheses, chronic stimulation under

742
00:41:49.910 --> 00:41:53.550
hypoxia does promote the accumulation of both mitochondrial

743
00:41:53.590 --> 00:41:57.400
citrate and cytosolic citrate, telling us that

744
00:41:57.470 --> 00:42:01.450
this metabolic pathway was occurring in the context of chronic

745
00:42:01.470 --> 00:42:05.062
stimulation.We also saw acetylation across the

746
00:42:05.102 --> 00:42:09.072
entire proteome. You can see this based on the laddering on

747
00:42:09.102 --> 00:42:11.722
this western blot, which we have tabulated here.

748
00:42:11.742 --> 00:42:14.722
And so we wanted to identify some of those hyperacetylated proteins.

749
00:42:14.972 --> 00:42:16.662
So we did this in our in vitro system.

750
00:42:17.522 --> 00:42:20.902
These data are still under analysis, but you can see many, many mitochondrial genes

751
00:42:22.062 --> 00:42:25.562
and metabolic proteins are hyperacetylated, but

752
00:42:25.642 --> 00:42:29.542
also really critical transcription factors in T cell biology, including

753
00:42:29.582 --> 00:42:31.162
the stemness factor TCF7,

754
00:42:32.002 --> 00:42:35.721
RUNX3, and BCF3. So both the metabolic

755
00:42:36.102 --> 00:42:39.842
and immunologic machinery is being hyperacetylated as a consequence

756
00:42:40.122 --> 00:42:42.082
of this altered metabolic pathway.

757
00:42:44.162 --> 00:42:47.342
So how does the citrate carrier contribute to T cell exhaustion?

758
00:42:47.942 --> 00:42:51.882
And so the way that we did this is by simply targeting SLC25A1, the gene

759
00:42:51.902 --> 00:42:55.122
that encodes the citrate carrier, and asking what happens.

760
00:42:56.002 --> 00:42:57.162
So we just used CRISPR

761
00:42:58.102 --> 00:43:02.062
to knock out this gene in T cells. Now, we then put them through the wringer

762
00:43:02.082 --> 00:43:03.982
and started doing metabolic profiling.

763
00:43:04.302 --> 00:43:07.502
And what I hope you can appreciate here, remember I showed you that respiratory

764
00:43:07.521 --> 00:43:11.042
capacity, that value of

765
00:43:11.062 --> 00:43:13.962
mitochondria that promotes longevity and increased

766
00:43:15.642 --> 00:43:16.482
responses to

767
00:43:17.522 --> 00:43:21.442
re-stimulation. When we knock out the citrate carrier and prevent the citrate

768
00:43:21.482 --> 00:43:25.342
from leaving the mitochondria, now we have a very

769
00:43:25.382 --> 00:43:29.082
superior oxidative phenotype with high respiratory capacity in these

770
00:43:29.122 --> 00:43:29.462
cells.

771
00:43:30.422 --> 00:43:33.742
But these cells also do more glycolysis as measured by the SEAR.

772
00:43:33.822 --> 00:43:37.362
So they're actually able to do better glucose metabolism as well, which at first

