00:55:45.048 --> 00:55:48.428
and it's my pleasure to be here today to talk to you about NK cell

1005
00:55:48.468 --> 00:55:52.458
metabolism and how we can reprogram it to enhance our adoptive cell therapy.

1006
00:55:53.728 --> 00:55:57.568
These are my disclosures. None of them are relevant for today's talk.

1007
00:55:58.568 --> 00:56:01.888
So we know that you've heard the tumor microenvironment is very

1008
00:56:02.148 --> 00:56:05.828
complex. Of course, there's interplay between various immune cells,

1009
00:56:05.948 --> 00:56:07.788
tumor cells, stromal cells, et cetera.

1010
00:56:07.828 --> 00:56:11.168
And there's a lot of metabolic competition

1011
00:56:11.408 --> 00:56:14.608
leading to scarce resources, so nutrient deprivation,

1012
00:56:14.708 --> 00:56:18.308
hypoxia, accumulation of lactate, which leads to acidosis,

1013
00:56:18.688 --> 00:56:22.428
accumulation of toxic metabolites, and all of these factors lead to

1014
00:56:22.468 --> 00:56:26.168
immunosuppression and suppression of the effector function of our

1015
00:56:26.268 --> 00:56:28.098
NK cells in the tumor microenvironment.

1016
00:56:28.958 --> 00:56:32.528
So in fact, we have some evidence from our clinical trials if we

1017
00:56:32.568 --> 00:56:34.248
compare the infusion product

1018
00:56:35.088 --> 00:56:38.608
before it goes into the patients and post-infusion

1019
00:56:38.648 --> 00:56:40.528
samples that we derive from the patients.

1020
00:56:40.628 --> 00:56:44.028
We see significant downregulation of key metabolic

1021
00:56:45.688 --> 00:56:49.048
processes, including oxidative phosphorylation, fatty acid metabolism,

1022
00:56:49.128 --> 00:56:52.848
glycolysis. And significant downregulation of key

1023
00:56:53.128 --> 00:56:57.108
signaling pathways such as mTOR, MEK, IL-2, STAT5, et cetera.

1024
00:56:58.028 --> 00:57:01.848
So these NK cells, once they enter the tumor microenvironment,

1025
00:57:01.928 --> 00:57:03.668
they are losing metabolic fitness and

1026
00:57:05.228 --> 00:57:06.348
becoming dysfunctional

1027
00:57:07.808 --> 00:57:11.408
following that. So there is a lot of metabolic competition between

1028
00:57:11.468 --> 00:57:15.368
tumor cells and immune effector cells because these cells rely on the same

1029
00:57:15.668 --> 00:57:19.208
resources. They really need amino acids, including glutamine,

1030
00:57:19.268 --> 00:57:22.768
glucose, fatty acids for them to grow and do their function.

1031
00:57:23.228 --> 00:57:26.927
And tumor cells have evolved to be very efficient at uptaking these

1032
00:57:26.968 --> 00:57:28.668
nutrients and metabolizing them.

1033
00:57:28.708 --> 00:57:32.138
So what's really happening is that the tumor cells are thriving, growing,

1034
00:57:32.608 --> 00:57:36.208
and starving the immune effector cells in the tumor microenvironment.

1035
00:57:36.218 --> 00:57:40.138
And what we're trying to do with our various immuno-metabolic strategies in the

1036
00:57:40.188 --> 00:57:43.608
lab is to skew this balance in favor of the immune effector

1037
00:57:43.648 --> 00:57:47.588
cells in order for them to work better in the tumor microenvironment

1038
00:57:47.628 --> 00:57:50.988
and outcompete the tumor cells. And there are multiple

1039
00:57:51.028 --> 00:57:54.948
opportunities to modulate immune effector cell metabolism before adoptive cell

1040
00:57:54.988 --> 00:57:57.578
therapy. You can do it at various stages.

1041
00:57:57.608 --> 00:58:00.448
You can even start from the choice of the starting material.

1042
00:58:00.528 --> 00:58:04.388
So the NK cell source really matters, and I'll show you a little bit of an example.

1043
00:58:05.208 --> 00:58:09.008
The vector design, the choice of the costimulatory molecule, the choice of the

1044
00:58:09.028 --> 00:58:12.868
cytokine payload, all of this plays into affects the

1045
00:58:12.908 --> 00:58:16.788
metabolism of the cells. And then the period of CAR manufacturing

1046
00:58:16.828 --> 00:58:19.708
and culturing, the ex vivo culturing period

1047
00:58:20.368 --> 00:58:24.148
provides a lot of opportunities for reprogramming the

1048
00:58:24.188 --> 00:58:28.028
metabolism of immune effector cells through the choice of cytokines

1049
00:58:28.088 --> 00:58:32.068
that you use to expand your cells, the media composition, and the nutrient

1050
00:58:32.168 --> 00:58:35.628
composition of the media, the use of various pharmacologic

1051
00:58:35.708 --> 00:58:39.388
modulators, inhibitors, and activators during the culturing system.

1052
00:58:39.908 --> 00:58:40.448
And then

1053
00:58:41.248 --> 00:58:42.948
playing with genetic modifications.

1054
00:58:43.008 --> 00:58:46.808
You've heard about CRISPR gene knockouts, and we're playing a lot

1055
00:58:46.868 --> 00:58:50.628
with CRISPR and gene overexpression in order to enhance

1056
00:58:50.808 --> 00:58:52.427
or downregulate certain

1057
00:58:53.588 --> 00:58:56.548
genes that are important for metabolic fitness of the cells.

1058
00:58:56.848 --> 00:59:00.748
And then finally, at the infusion stage, you're able also to combine

1059
00:59:00.808 --> 00:59:04.588
your immune effector cells with varied pharmacologic combinations in order

1060
00:59:04.648 --> 00:59:06.828
to optimize their metabolic function.

1061
00:59:07.288 --> 00:59:10.688
So I'll start with a little bit of a snippet on the starting material.

1062
00:59:10.968 --> 00:59:14.688
This is in collaboration with Dr. Ken Cheng group at MD Anderson.

1063
00:59:14.748 --> 00:59:18.528
Bakul Mohanty and Mervie Dede did this single-cell RNA sequencing

1064
00:59:18.568 --> 00:59:22.388
analysis where they compared cord blood NK cells versus peripheral

1065
00:59:22.468 --> 00:59:26.448
blood NK cells, and there are certain clusters you can see in

1066
00:59:26.488 --> 00:59:30.388
the single-cell RNA seq that are very enriched in cord blood compared

1067
00:59:30.488 --> 00:59:33.248
to peripheral blood. And when we focus on these

1068
00:59:34.388 --> 00:59:38.148
clusters, clusters six, seven, and eight, we can see they're highly enriched in

1069
00:59:38.228 --> 00:59:42.088
various metabolic pathways compared to clusters

1070
00:59:42.168 --> 00:59:43.728
that are enriched in peripheral blood.

1071
00:59:43.948 --> 00:59:47.788
And when we look at the number of differentially expressed metabolic processes in

1072
00:59:47.848 --> 00:59:51.748
these cord blood enriched clusters, they're much higher compared to the peripheral

1073
00:59:51.808 --> 00:59:52.068
blood

1074
00:59:53.088 --> 00:59:56.508
enriched clusters. And at the product level, the cord blood

1075
00:59:56.768 --> 00:59:57.588
NK cells

1076
00:59:58.908 --> 01:00:01.988
show this metabolic diversity compared to peripheral blood.

1077
01:00:02.268 --> 01:00:06.208
This is better portrayed here in the circus plot, where cord blood in red is

1078
01:00:06.248 --> 01:00:09.968
showing enrichment in amino acid metabolism, carbohydrate metabolism,

1079
01:00:10.028 --> 01:00:13.808
lipid metabolism, et cetera. So they're much more

1080
01:00:14.068 --> 01:00:17.938
metabolically diverse compared to peripheral blood NK cells, and we're

1081
01:00:17.988 --> 01:00:21.068
studying that further in the lab and validating it at the functional

1082
01:00:21.108 --> 01:00:24.978
level. So moving on to some of the strategies we've

1083
01:00:25.088 --> 01:00:28.896
used in theCAR manufacturing and culturing stage, we

1084
01:00:29.036 --> 01:00:31.476
played a little bit with nutrient composition of the media.

1085
01:00:31.856 --> 01:00:35.716
This is work done by a very talented postdoc in the lab, Silvia Tiberti,

1086
01:00:36.056 --> 01:00:39.776
who's here and who's going to be presenting her poster tomorrow.

1087
01:00:40.096 --> 01:00:44.026
But basically, instead of growing NK cells with the regular

1088
01:00:44.136 --> 01:00:47.316
NK cell media, which is either RPMI clicks or

1089
01:00:47.476 --> 01:00:51.216
SCGM, she cultured the NK cells in this APEL media.

1090
01:00:51.576 --> 01:00:55.516
APEL media is usually used in iPSC differentiation

1091
01:00:55.616 --> 01:00:59.476
during embryoid body formation. And she chose that media just because

1092
01:00:59.536 --> 01:01:03.476
its composition, it's very enriched in essential lipids such

1093
01:01:03.556 --> 01:01:07.236
as oleic acid, linoleic acid, cholesterol, et cetera, and she was

1094
01:01:07.276 --> 01:01:09.616
curious to see what it would do to the NK cells.

1095
01:01:09.976 --> 01:01:13.936
So she cultured the NK cells, whether they are non-transduced or transduced with

1096
01:01:13.956 --> 01:01:17.836
the CD70 CAR NK cells with a CD70 CAR vector,

1097
01:01:19.356 --> 01:01:21.216
and then looked at their metabolism.

1098
01:01:21.336 --> 01:01:24.836
And both mitochondrial mass and potential were enriched in the

1099
01:01:24.896 --> 01:01:28.316
APEL-grown NK cells compared to the standard media.

1100
01:01:28.766 --> 01:01:31.016
And you can see here by confocal imaging,

1101
01:01:31.956 --> 01:01:35.836
these mitochondria are more elongated, they're aggregated,

1102
01:01:35.896 --> 01:01:39.856
they're polarized compared to mitochondria of NK cells grown

1103
01:01:39.896 --> 01:01:43.636
in standard media, where they are more rounded, more dispersed in

1104
01:01:43.696 --> 01:01:44.836
this perinuclear

1105
01:01:45.936 --> 01:01:48.716
disposition. And then when she looked functionally,

1106
01:01:48.896 --> 01:01:52.436
these NK cells grown in APEL media show

1107
01:01:52.476 --> 01:01:54.676
enhanced oxidative phosphorylation.

1108
01:01:54.756 --> 01:01:57.976
Both basal respiration and spare respiratory capacity are increased.

1109
01:01:58.306 --> 01:02:01.456
And when she performed some metabolic flexibility assays,

1110
01:02:02.196 --> 01:02:05.516
she saw that the NK cells, after inhibiting certain

1111
01:02:06.296 --> 01:02:10.136
metabolic pathways individually, the NK cells grown in regular

1112
01:02:10.236 --> 01:02:13.296
NK cell media are suffering, basically decreasing maximal

1113
01:02:13.316 --> 01:02:17.106
respiration significantly, whereas the NK cells grown in

1114
01:02:17.136 --> 01:02:20.756
APEL media are maintaining a high level of maximal

1115
01:02:20.816 --> 01:02:24.436
respiration. So without any genetic engineering, she was able to

1116
01:02:24.476 --> 01:02:27.656
generate cells with improved metabolic fitness.

1117
01:02:28.636 --> 01:02:31.136
And then does that translate to better functionality?

1118
01:02:31.256 --> 01:02:34.376
Silvia has a lot of data that she can show you in her poster, but this is just an

1119
01:02:34.416 --> 01:02:38.076
example of one of her re-challenge assays that she performed

1120
01:02:38.116 --> 01:02:41.416
against MOLM14, which is an AML leukemia cell

1121
01:02:41.476 --> 01:02:44.776
line. Basically, this is a re-challenge assay, so every

1122
01:02:44.816 --> 01:02:47.856
two to three days she adds tumor again.

1123
01:02:48.136 --> 01:02:49.856
The lower the curve, the better the killing.

1124
01:02:49.896 --> 01:02:53.596
You see the APEL-grown NK cells are performing much better here in

1125
01:02:53.676 --> 01:02:56.696
purple compared to NK cells grown in regular media.

1126
01:02:57.065 --> 01:03:00.776
And this, she has data in various tumor

1127
01:03:00.816 --> 01:03:02.446
models, including solid tumors,

1128
01:03:03.416 --> 01:03:06.736
pancreatic cancer, ovarian cancer, et cetera, so it's not disease specific.

1129
01:03:07.186 --> 01:03:10.946
And then in vivo, they perform much better and lead to survival advantage in the

1130
01:03:11.016 --> 01:03:14.616
mice. And then when she extracted these NK cells from the

1131
01:03:14.656 --> 01:03:17.636
mice and looked at their metabolic

1132
01:03:18.616 --> 01:03:22.186
capacity, they still retain their metabolic advantage with higher

1133
01:03:22.256 --> 01:03:24.036
mitochondrial mass and potential.

1134
01:03:24.076 --> 01:03:27.316
So it's not just when they're cultured in the media.

1135
01:03:27.716 --> 01:03:31.516
They're having some form of epigenetic remodeling, and she

1136
01:03:31.576 --> 01:03:34.996
has data through ATAC-seq looking at their

1137
01:03:35.036 --> 01:03:35.806
epigenetic

1138
01:03:37.016 --> 01:03:40.316
function, basically. So the media is reprogramming the NK

1139
01:03:40.456 --> 01:03:44.396
cells at the epigenetic level and metabolic level

1140
01:03:44.416 --> 01:03:48.356
in order to enhance their persistence and improve the cytotoxic activity.

1141
01:03:48.856 --> 01:03:52.676
This is her working model. So basically she's created this metabolically

1142
01:03:52.816 --> 01:03:56.476
primed NK cells through just changing the

1143
01:03:56.536 --> 01:04:00.356
media, basically enhancing their metabolic fitness, cytotoxic activity,

1144
01:04:00.456 --> 01:04:04.356
proliferation, et cetera. And if you're interested to know more, please visit her

1145
01:04:04.396 --> 01:04:06.996
poster. She's speaking tomorrow morning.

1146
01:04:08.596 --> 01:04:12.496
So now moving on to some other strategies we've used in the lab.

1147
01:04:12.676 --> 01:04:16.596
CRISPR gene editing has been a big part of our journey, combining it with CAR

1148
01:04:16.656 --> 01:04:20.616
modification. So one of the first metabolic checkpoints we went

1149
01:04:20.796 --> 01:04:23.796
after was CIS or cytokine-inducible SH2-containing

1150
01:04:23.916 --> 01:04:27.776
protein. This was a few years ago, so I won't spend too much time, and

1151
01:04:27.796 --> 01:04:31.316
it's published. But basically, it's a major metabolic checkpoint in NK cells

1152
01:04:31.676 --> 01:04:35.556
that acts as a negative regulator of JAK-STAT signaling downstream of

1153
01:04:35.656 --> 01:04:36.696
IL-2 and IL-15.

1154
01:04:37.786 --> 01:04:41.296
It's highly upregulated in our CAR NK cells

1155
01:04:41.336 --> 01:04:45.236
because all our CAR NK cells include interleukin-15, which

1156
01:04:45.276 --> 01:04:47.436
basically upregulates this metabolic checkpoint.

1157
01:04:47.516 --> 01:04:51.136
When we knock it out, we enrich for

1158
01:04:51.156 --> 01:04:54.816
mTOR signaling, glycolysis, interferon gamma response, IL-2,

1159
01:04:54.876 --> 01:04:55.876
STAT5, which is

1160
01:04:57.916 --> 01:05:01.596
expected since it's a negative regulator of JAK-STAT signaling.

1161
01:05:01.676 --> 01:05:05.656
But when we use these cells, basically for adoptive cell

1162
01:05:05.736 --> 01:05:09.256
therapy in mice model, they really make a big difference in

1163
01:05:09.316 --> 01:05:11.266
multiple models. This is here in a

1164
01:05:11.336 --> 01:05:15.306
very aggressive Raji lymphoma mouse

1165
01:05:15.356 --> 01:05:17.866
model that's non-curative, and we had really

1166
01:05:18.816 --> 01:05:20.916
significant improvement in survival in these mice.

1167
01:05:20.996 --> 01:05:22.656
So by basically

1168
01:05:24.176 --> 01:05:28.116
deleting a metabolic checkpoint, we're able to rewire these cells in order for

1169
01:05:28.136 --> 01:05:30.836
them to function better in the tumor microenvironment.

1170
01:05:30.866 --> 01:05:34.036
Another major negative regulator that we focus on a lot is

1171
01:05:34.076 --> 01:05:37.076
TGF-beta, which is what we call old but gold.

1172
01:05:37.136 --> 01:05:39.856
It's really not very sexy, but it's very important.

1173
01:05:39.916 --> 01:05:41.556
It's a major

1174
01:05:42.916 --> 01:05:46.776
immunosuppressant for NK cells and other immune effector

1175
01:05:46.796 --> 01:05:50.436
cells in the tumor microenvironment of both hematologic malignancies and solid

1176
01:05:50.516 --> 01:05:54.496
tumors. And in addition to it being an immunosuppressant,

1177
01:05:54.556 --> 01:05:58.256
it's a major metabolic regulator because TGF-beta has been shown to have

1178
01:05:58.266 --> 01:06:01.936
direct inhibitory effect on mTOR, decreasing glycolysis, and

1179
01:06:01.976 --> 01:06:05.596
direct inhibitory effect on OXPHOS due to its

1180
01:06:05.656 --> 01:06:08.624
effects on complex one and complex four.So,

1181
01:06:09.344 --> 01:06:13.224
recently we've published that TGF-beta plays a very important role

1182
01:06:13.264 --> 01:06:14.044
in AML,

1183
01:06:15.264 --> 01:06:18.964
NK cell functions. So NK cells from AML and MDS

1184
01:06:19.024 --> 01:06:20.604
patients are very dysfunctional.

1185
01:06:21.024 --> 01:06:23.904
They don't kill, basically, AML cells.

1186
01:06:23.964 --> 01:06:26.844
They also have very altered metabolism.

1187
01:06:27.104 --> 01:06:30.724
And a big part of their dysfunction, we showed that is related to

1188
01:06:30.784 --> 01:06:34.624
TGF-beta signaling. Again, this work is published, so I won't be

1189
01:06:34.764 --> 01:06:38.384
spending too much time on it. But basically, through a cell-cell contact dependent

1190
01:06:38.444 --> 01:06:42.104
mechanism, TGF-beta gets released from the myeloid blast,

1191
01:06:42.204 --> 01:06:45.744
binding to the TGF-beta receptor complex, leading to phosphorylation of

1192
01:06:45.764 --> 01:06:49.664
SMAD2/3. This complex then translocates to the nucleus and

1193
01:06:49.724 --> 01:06:53.464
upregulates a transcription factor called BATF that basically

1194
01:06:53.524 --> 01:06:57.224
rewires the whole-- leads to an epigenetic reprogramming of the cells,

1195
01:06:57.304 --> 01:06:58.874
leading to irreversible dysfunction.

1196
01:06:59.224 --> 01:07:02.874
To prevent that, we went after the TGF-beta receptor II,

1197
01:07:03.264 --> 01:07:07.204
CRISPRed it out, and combined it with our CAR transduction, and

1198
01:07:07.244 --> 01:07:10.544
we've created, really, NK cells that function much better in vivo

1199
01:07:11.224 --> 01:07:12.724
in leukemia models,

1200
01:07:13.564 --> 01:07:15.924
as you can see here in this example.

1201
01:07:15.984 --> 01:07:19.584
So with that work, preclinical work, we took this

1202
01:07:19.644 --> 01:07:23.344
approach to the clinic. And this is a Phase 1/2 clinical

1203
01:07:23.464 --> 01:07:27.254
trial that is now open and enrolling at MD Anderson, testing the safety and

1204
01:07:27.324 --> 01:07:31.304
efficacy of TGF-beta receptor II knockout CD70 CAR NK cells

1205
01:07:31.624 --> 01:07:34.954
for the treatment of relapsed refractory AML. It's led by Dr.

1206
01:07:35.184 --> 01:07:38.904
Nick Short in the leukemia department. It's basically a dose escalation phase.

1207
01:07:39.964 --> 01:07:43.644
Patients would receive flucytosine for depletion, and then on day zero

1208
01:07:43.704 --> 01:07:46.804
receive these off-the-shelf, completely frozen

1209
01:07:47.504 --> 01:07:49.204
CD70 CAR NK cells.

1210
01:07:50.924 --> 01:07:54.744
Yes. And then this approach also with the same cell bank,

1211
01:07:54.884 --> 01:07:58.184
we opened another clinical trial

1212
01:07:58.704 --> 01:08:02.384
for the treatment of relapsed refractory renal cell carcinoma, since

1213
01:08:02.424 --> 01:08:06.114
TGF-beta is also a very important metabolic suppressant and

1214
01:08:06.164 --> 01:08:09.924
immunosuppressant in the solid tumor microenvironment, and specifically

1215
01:08:10.004 --> 01:08:13.064
renal cell carcinoma. This trial is led by Dr. Pablos M.

1216
01:08:13.144 --> 01:08:15.964
Sawal in the GU department at MD Anderson.

1217
01:08:16.004 --> 01:08:19.804
It's also open and enrolling, and the same design, basically, with

1218
01:08:19.844 --> 01:08:23.824
dose escalation. Okay, so now moving on to some unpublished

1219
01:08:23.945 --> 01:08:27.084
work with gene overexpression that we're very excited about.

1220
01:08:27.445 --> 01:08:31.174
This strategy was inspired by how viruses, when they

1221
01:08:31.244 --> 01:08:35.124
infect host cells, they can hijack the metabolism of these

1222
01:08:35.144 --> 01:08:38.105
host cells for their own purposes in order to make more viral

1223
01:08:38.204 --> 01:08:41.804
particles. And each virus does it in a specific way.

1224
01:08:42.224 --> 01:08:45.964
A human adenovirus uses this gene called E4ORF1,

1225
01:08:46.084 --> 01:08:48.644
or early region four open reading frame one.

1226
01:08:49.204 --> 01:08:52.684
And when it's translated, this protein, basically, what it does, it

1227
01:08:52.844 --> 01:08:56.724
binds to PI3KDLG1 in a trimeric complex

1228
01:08:56.784 --> 01:08:57.485
on the inner

1229
01:08:58.605 --> 01:09:02.364
cell membrane. It phosphorylates AKT, activates mTOR,

1230
01:09:02.724 --> 01:09:06.464
and then E4ORF1 also binds to making the nucleus leading to increase in

1231
01:09:06.504 --> 01:09:08.824
MYC-dependent biosynthetic pathways.

1232
01:09:08.884 --> 01:09:12.544
This has been published in the setting of infection, of adenovirus

1233
01:09:12.605 --> 01:09:16.525
infection. So how after the adenovirus infects the whole cell, what does

1234
01:09:16.544 --> 01:09:20.434
it do to its metabolism? And then we were inspired by this and said,

1235
01:09:20.485 --> 01:09:24.235
"Why don't we introduce this gene in our NK cells and see what happens?"

1236
01:09:24.364 --> 01:09:28.084
Basically, the hypothesis was, if we introduce that gene in the NK cells, we're

1237
01:09:28.164 --> 01:09:31.065
able to increase their metabolic fitness, their

1238
01:09:31.684 --> 01:09:35.464
flexibility, enhancing their OXPHOS, glycolysis, enhancing their

1239
01:09:35.504 --> 01:09:39.464
competition with the tumors, and eventually leading to better cytotoxicity in the

1240
01:09:39.504 --> 01:09:43.384
tumor microenvironment. And indeed, these E4ORF1 engineered NK

1241
01:09:43.424 --> 01:09:47.155
cells show very significant enhancement in glycolysis and

1242
01:09:47.464 --> 01:09:49.364
increase in oxidative phosphorylation.

1243
01:09:49.804 --> 01:09:53.664
And what's interesting, their mitochondrial mass and potential are

1244
01:09:53.704 --> 01:09:55.644
both increased, but under starvation.

1245
01:09:55.684 --> 01:09:59.664
You can see that very evident here in the confocal imaging, where under

1246
01:09:59.724 --> 01:10:02.864
regular conditions, maybe there's a little bit of an increase, but under

1247
01:10:02.944 --> 01:10:06.684
starvation, these cells significantly enhance

1248
01:10:06.724 --> 01:10:10.524
their mitochondrial potential, and the mitochondrial area

1249
01:10:10.644 --> 01:10:14.204
is much more increased compared to the control NK

1250
01:10:14.264 --> 01:10:18.064
cells. At the signaling level, these E4ORF1 engineered NK

1251
01:10:18.144 --> 01:10:22.124
cells upregulate key enzymes related to glycolysis, both at

1252
01:10:22.244 --> 01:10:25.584
steady-state conditions and after stimulation with CD16.

1253
01:10:25.924 --> 01:10:29.544
So hexokinase 2, LDHA are both increased significantly.

1254
01:10:30.384 --> 01:10:32.364
With glutaminolysis also, these

1255
01:10:33.724 --> 01:10:37.564
engineered NK cells show enhancement in SLC1A5

1256
01:10:37.684 --> 01:10:41.484
expression and glutaminase expression, and then also they

1257
01:10:41.584 --> 01:10:45.444
show increase in CD36 and CPT1A expression, so fatty

1258
01:10:45.484 --> 01:10:47.464
acid metabolism is also affected.

1259
01:10:47.484 --> 01:10:51.444
So you can see it's not really leading to a single pathway improvement.

1260
01:10:51.684 --> 01:10:54.984
It's doing this multimodal increase in metabolic

1261
01:10:55.064 --> 01:10:57.444
pathways like viruses usually do.

1262
01:10:58.744 --> 01:11:02.524
And then at the transcriptomic level, when we compared E4ORF1 engineered NK

1263
01:11:02.564 --> 01:11:06.464
cells to control NK cells, they show enrichment in various inflammatory

1264
01:11:06.504 --> 01:11:10.384
pathways, interferon alpha response, interferon gamma response,

1265
01:11:11.044 --> 01:11:13.744
JAK-STAT signaling, IL2, STAT5, et cetera.

1266
01:11:14.364 --> 01:11:18.164
And interestingly, all these pathways remain

1267
01:11:18.224 --> 01:11:21.884
enriched even under glucose starvation, glutamine starvation, or

1268
01:11:21.944 --> 01:11:23.004
lipid starvation.

1269
01:11:24.664 --> 01:11:28.484
This translates to better killing capacity against various solid tumor cell

1270
01:11:28.524 --> 01:11:32.364
lines, including colorectal carcinoma, triple-negative breast cancer, pancreatic

1271
01:11:32.404 --> 01:11:35.764
adenocarcinoma, renal cell carcinomas, and many others.

1272
01:11:35.824 --> 01:11:39.764
So this is not disease specific. These E4ORF1 engineered NK cells

1273
01:11:39.804 --> 01:11:43.784
are able to enhance the killing efficacy of our NK cells

1274
01:11:43.824 --> 01:11:46.464
in multiple models, and they're able to do

1275
01:11:47.384 --> 01:11:49.224
so even under starved conditions.

1276
01:11:49.304 --> 01:11:52.484
So under glutamine starvation or glucose starvations, these cells

1277
01:11:53.824 --> 01:11:55.544
maintain their advantage in killing.

1278
01:11:56.524 --> 01:11:59.764
And then we thought about what could be common to all.

1279
01:11:59.884 --> 01:12:03.404
What could beUpstream of all these metabolic

1280
01:12:03.444 --> 01:12:04.544
pathways that could be

1281
01:12:05.584 --> 01:12:09.464
enriching for this metabolic fitness, we thought of

1282
01:12:09.504 --> 01:12:13.434
AMP kinase as a central nutrient sensor in the cell, and we saw that

1283
01:12:13.464 --> 01:12:17.304
E4ORF1 really increases phosphorylation of AMP kinase alpha

1284
01:12:17.384 --> 01:12:20.824
and total AMP kinase alpha expression in the cells.

1285
01:12:20.884 --> 01:12:24.804
And then we see here, this is a spheroid assay, so incucyte

1286
01:12:24.864 --> 01:12:28.144
live-cell imaging with spheroids labeled with GFP.

1287
01:12:28.584 --> 01:12:32.344
You can see the controls, the non-transduced, and the empty vector NK cells do not

1288
01:12:32.444 --> 01:12:36.144
function very well. When you introduce the E4ORF1 NK cells, they kill

1289
01:12:36.204 --> 01:12:36.744
really well.

1290
01:12:37.704 --> 01:12:41.124
After five days, you can see complete ablation of the tumor.

1291
01:12:41.514 --> 01:12:45.244
But in the presence of AMP kinase inhibition, this phenotype is completely

1292
01:12:45.344 --> 01:12:49.254
abrogated. So basically, AMP kinase is playing a central

1293
01:12:49.304 --> 01:12:53.044
role in mediating the phenotype of E4ORF1 in this setting.

1294
01:12:54.264 --> 01:12:57.844
Then we ask ourself, is this still relevant in the CAR setting?

1295
01:12:58.064 --> 01:13:01.624
Because the CAR NK cells, the CAR itself can modulate the

1296
01:13:01.644 --> 01:13:05.564
metabolism, the interleukin 15 that's present in our CARs also

1297
01:13:05.604 --> 01:13:09.584
modulate metabolism. So is E4ORF1 still relevant in

1298
01:13:09.624 --> 01:13:13.524
that setting? And we saw that even CAR-engineered NK

1299
01:13:13.584 --> 01:13:17.164
cells that express E4ORF1 have increase in

1300
01:13:17.184 --> 01:13:19.644
glycolysis and oxidative phosphorylation.

1301
01:13:19.684 --> 01:13:23.524
They have improved capacity for serial killing and serial rechallenge

1302
01:13:23.664 --> 01:13:26.924
assays, and they lead to better outcomes in our mouse models.

1303
01:13:27.244 --> 01:13:31.063
And if you're interested to know more about the mechanism, please visit

1304
01:13:31.144 --> 01:13:32.084
Madison Moore's

1305
01:13:33.284 --> 01:13:36.884
poster tomorrow morning. He's going to be talking to you more about that.

1306
01:13:36.964 --> 01:13:40.834
So in conclusion, there are really multiple strategies to reprogram NK cell

1307
01:13:40.844 --> 01:13:44.724
metabolism. I've touched on some of the approaches we're

1308
01:13:44.924 --> 01:13:46.724
doing in the lab, but there are many more

1309
01:13:47.844 --> 01:13:51.564
that we're trying, and we're very excited these strategies can be really leveraged

1310
01:13:51.624 --> 01:13:55.064
to enhance the persistence and the efficacy of NK cells to

1311
01:13:55.324 --> 01:13:58.884
overcome some of the challenges in the TME and improve the outcomes of our

1312
01:13:58.944 --> 01:14:00.484
adoptive cell therapy approaches.

